101
00:06:14.248 --> 00:06:18.961
is difficult to implement on the quantum
hardware because of large circuit depths.

102
00:06:19.754 --> 00:06:23.132
Generally, calculations
can be more successful if you can,

103
00:06:23.466 --> 00:06:27.512
first of all choose a reference state
and initial set of parameters

104
00:06:27.720 --> 00:06:31.057
that create an ansatz state
close to the ground state.

105
00:06:31.349 --> 00:06:35.436
And second, avoid unnecessary parameters.

106
00:06:36.104 --> 00:06:39.857
These either introduce
greater circuit depth with no payoff

107
00:06:40.149 --> 00:06:42.944
or create a larger parameter space

108
00:06:43.152 --> 00:06:46.239
to search leading to plateaus
in the classical optimization.

109
00:06:47.532 --> 00:06:49.992
What parameters are necessary is a problem

110
00:06:49.992 --> 00:06:53.121
specific question
that requires careful thought.

111
00:06:53.955 --> 00:06:56.082
Let's talk about where our guest of honor,

112
00:06:56.499 --> 00:06:59.043
the Hamiltonian, is hiding in all of this.

113
00:06:59.544 --> 00:07:02.964
As we learned in the previous section,
the Hamiltonian after qubit

114
00:07:02.964 --> 00:07:07.677
mapping is represented as a sum of
weighted strings of Pauli operators.

115
00:07:08.386 --> 00:07:11.681
Eventually, however,
we want to evaluate the expectation

116
00:07:11.681 --> 00:07:16.561
value of our Hamiltonian on the ansatz
state produced by the variational form.

117
00:07:17.103 --> 00:07:20.022
Luckily, quantum
mechanics is nice and linear

118
00:07:20.189 --> 00:07:23.025
and this is what we'll use
to get the expectation value.

119
00:07:23.693 --> 00:07:24.986
This is how it works.

120
00:07:24.986 --> 00:07:28.114
We know the Hamiltonian is a weighted
sum of Paulis

121
00:07:28.573 --> 00:07:31.742
because of linearity
the expectation value of the sum

122
00:07:31.993 --> 00:07:36.372
is equal to the sum of the expectation
values of each Pauli string.

123
00:07:36.831 --> 00:07:41.252
Well, this is great because as you already
know, measuring in the Pauli basis

124
00:07:41.419 --> 00:07:45.673
is as simple as a rotation
of a standard measurement basis.

125
00:07:46.215 --> 00:07:50.595
Instead of measuring the expectation value
on this huge Hamiltonian represented

126
00:07:50.595 --> 00:07:55.183
as a sum, we first evaluate expectation
values of individual terms

127
00:07:55.391 --> 00:07:58.186
and sum at the end
with corresponding weights.

128
00:07:59.061 --> 00:08:01.355
This is why in many resources

129
00:08:01.522 --> 00:08:04.734
you will see only single qubit rotations
after the ansatz.

130
00:08:05.109 --> 00:08:09.614
This is what implements the Hamiltonian
in every execution of the circuit.

131
00:08:10.573 --> 00:08:11.741
In the next video,

132
00:08:11.741 --> 00:08:15.161
we'll explore what happens
during the classical optimization step.

133
00:08:15.703 --> 00:08:16.912
I'll see you there.
